title: Kosterhavet National Park
text:
Kosterhavet National Park (, literally "The Koster Sea National Park") is the first <a href="List%20of%20national%20parks%20of%20Sweden">national</a> <a href="marine%20park">marine park</a> in Sweden, inaugurated on September 2009. It is part of the <a href="Skagerrak">Skagerrak</a> sea and is located in <a href="Str%C3%B6mstad%20Municipality">Strömstad</a> and <a href="Tanum%20Municipality">Tanum</a> municipalities in <a href="Bohusl%C3%A4n">Bohuslän</a>, <a href="V%C3%A4stra%20G%C3%B6taland%20County">Västra Götaland County</a>, <a href="Sweden">Sweden</a>. It consists of the sea and shores around the <a href="Koster%20Islands">Koster Islands</a>, excluding everything else on the islands. In the north, it borders the <a href="Norway">Norwegian</a> marine park of <a href="Ytre%20Hvaler%20National%20Park">Ytre Hvaler</a>.
Kosterhavet National Park is home to Sweden's largest seal colony.
Nature.
The environment in the park is unique to Swedish waters. Over 6,000 marine species have been identified, about 200 of them can not to be found elsewhere in Sweden. The Kosterfjord () is deep with relatively low temperature – – and high <a href="salinity">salinity</a> (about 35%). <a href="Brachiopod">Brachiopod</a>, <a href="sponge">sponge</a> and <a href="Lophelia">coral</a> larvae are brought in by currents from the Atlantic. Rare seabirds, such as <a href="Arctic%20tern">Arctic tern</a>s and <a href="skua">skua</a>s, along with a large population of <a href="harbor%20seal">harbor seal</a>s have their habitat here. <a href="Plaice">Plaice</a>, <a href="cod">cod</a> and <a href="brown%20trout">sea trout</a> breed in the more shallow waters closer to the shore.
Professional fishing is allowed although special regulations apply. The waters of the park is significant for the fishing of "<a href="Pandalus%20borealis">northern prawn</a>" and <a href="Nephrops%20norvegicus">Norwegian lobster</a>. Fishing is not subject to environmental protection, and are instead regulated by fishery laws and an agreement from 2000.
